    <section id="the-deeper-point" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Deeper Point</h2>

      <p>The vagus nerve is not a wellness trend. It is a central organizing structure of how the body regulates itself — connecting organ systems that medicine has historically treated in isolation, transmitting information that shapes cognition, emotion, and immunity simultaneously.</p>

      <p>What's new is not the nerve. It has been in the anatomy textbooks for centuries. What's new is a growing mechanistic understanding of what it actually does: that the gut is talking to the brain in ways that matter for memory; that the inflammatory response is neurally regulated through a dedicated reflex arc; that the body is a more integrated system than the specialist model of medicine tends to acknowledge.</p>

      <p>The Stanford findings are a striking example of what happens when you follow that integration all the way down. A bacterium in the gut wall produces a metabolite that activates an immune cell that silences a nerve that stops talking to a brain region responsible for memory. Remove any link in that chain, and the old mice remember. Add years of chronic inflammation, poor diet, and sedentary behavior, and the chain is severed before the brain ever knew it was under threat.</p>

      <p>That's not just a story about aging mice. That's a description of how cognitive decline may begin in the body, long before it shows up in the mind.</p>
    </section>

